We cannot say with certainty who this predecessor was: but many reasons, which need not be given here in detail, point to the Rhodian Posidonius, who is spoken of in the note to l. 3. 6. and who, as Cicero says in that passage, had been his teachcr: and doubtless the teacher of Balbus also. since Cotta 1. 44, 123, calls him familiare& omnium nostrum. His work περὶ θεῶν was one of con- siderable extent: Diogenes Laertius, Vll, 138, cites the thirteenth book ; so that Cicero gave only a short extract. It is possible. though we have no evidence. that he also made use of other Stoic writings. All that he cites from Zeno, Cleanthes, Chrysippus and Panaetius. even if he had ever read thern, he might have found in Posidonius: and even what he says in 11, 34 of the sphere of Posidonius could have been found in the same author. He however differs from him in some particulam, as for example the size of the moon, 11, 40, 103: and the whole astronomical part 0f§ 104 appears to have been worked up independently. Of course the etymologies of the Latin names of the gods, 11. 26, 27, as well as the examples from Roman history are Cicero's own, given perhaps in place of others used by Posidonius.¹ Besides in 1, 44, 123 he himself cites the fifth book of Posidonius De Mztura Deorum.
